WEBVTT

00:00:01.920 --> 00:00:09.680
<v Teacher>So we saw how our "to" form of the verb: to come, to eat,

00:00:10.460 --> 00:00:17.099
<v Teacher><i>to tolerate</i>. How would <i>to tolerate</i> be?

00:00:17.099 --> 00:00:20.360
<v Student><i>Toleration</i>-<b>toleración</b>-<b>tolerar</b>.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:21.560
<v Teacher>Exactly, <b>tolerar</b>.

00:00:21.560 --> 00:00:21.880
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:21.880 --> 00:00:25.880
<v Teacher>So our "to" form ends with an <i>r</i> and it's always going to be <i>-ar</i>,

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:31.880
<v Teacher><i>-er</i> or <i>-ir</i>. And we had an example of each.

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:41.160
<v Teacher>And we notice that for <i>-ar</i>, <i>-ir</i> and <i>-er</i> verbs, unless the verb is irregular, we will take off that ending

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:48.800
<v Teacher>and put on an <i>-o</i> to get the "I" version, to say <i>I tolerate</i> for example. So how would you say <i>I tolerate</i>?

00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:51.340
<v Student><b>Tolero</b>?

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:52.620
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:56.780
<v Teacher>And you moved the accent back as well, which is essential for the present tense.

00:00:56.780 --> 00:00:57.340
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:00:57.340 --> 00:01:01.580
<v Teacher>If you said <b>toleró</b>, it would mean <i>he tolerated</i>,

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:05.320
<v Teacher>which as I mentioned, will be useful for us later when we learn this tense.

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:11.160
<v Teacher>But it's important in the present tense to have the accent on the penultimate syllable. <b>Tolero</b>.

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:13.000
<v Teacher>What was <i>to eat</i>?

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:14.080
<v Student><b>Comer.</b>

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:16.080
<v Teacher>And what is <i>I eat</i>?

00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:18.240
<v Student><b>Comero.</b>

00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:22.160
<v Teacher>So you don't add on the <i>o</i>, you take off the ending – and then you put:

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:22.520
<v Student>Oh yes, <b>como</b>.

00:01:22.520 --> 00:01:24.520
<v Teacher><b>Como.</b> Good.

00:01:24.520 --> 00:01:27.880
<v Teacher>This also means <i>how</i> or <i>like</i>, by coincidence.

00:01:27.880 --> 00:01:29.720
<v Teacher>You might have heard <b>cómo estás</b>?

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:30.520
<v Teacher><i>How are you?</i>

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:32.920
<v Teacher>But <b>como</b> is also <i>I eat</i>.

00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:39.259
<v Teacher>So for all verbs, we take off the ending and we add <i>-o</i> and we get the "I" version.

00:01:39.259 --> 00:01:44.540
<v Teacher>But for the rest of the versions, for <i>he</i>, <i>she</i>, <i>it</i>, <i>you</i> (formal), for <i>we</i>, etc.,

00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:47.659
<v Teacher>the verbs split into two groups.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:52.280
<v Teacher>Although we have three different endings, we have two groups.

00:01:52.280 --> 00:01:57.240
<v Teacher>Now most verbs in Spanish are <i>-ar</i> verbs.

00:01:57.020 --> 00:02:01.420
<v Teacher>This is the biggest group. The group of <i>-ar</i> verbs, the verbs that end <i>-ar</i>.

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:09.580
<v Teacher>In fact any new verb that comes into Spanish will become, will be crowned, as an <i>-ar</i> verb.

00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:13.200
<v Teacher>So to give you some examples - <b>tuitear</b>.

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:14.800
<v Teacher>What do you think that means?

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:15.760
<v Student><i>To Twitter</i>.

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:18.080
<v Teacher><i>To tweet</i>, yes, <b>tuitear</b>.

00:02:18.459 --> 00:02:22.140
<v Teacher><b>Facebookear</b>, yes this exists.

00:02:22.140 --> 00:02:23.980
<v Teacher><b>Googlear</b>.

00:02:23.980 --> 00:02:24.939
<v Student>Excellent.

00:02:24.939 --> 00:02:32.459
<v Teacher>So there is something in the mental lexicon, in the mental dictionary that is saying there can be no more <i>-er</i>/<i>-ir</i> verbs.

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:33.300
<v Teacher>These are a historic group,

00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:34.660
<v Teacher>the door is closed.

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:36.420
<v Teacher>So we have two groups.

00:02:36.420 --> 00:02:43.700
<v Teacher>So for <i>-ar</i>, <i>-er</i>, <i>-ir</i>, if the verb is regular we take off the ending <i>-ar</i>, <i>-er</i>, <i>-ir</i>, and we put <i>-o</i> and we get the "I" version.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:50.060
<v Teacher>Now for the others, the other versions, there's a slight difference between <i>-ar</i> verbs and <i>-er</i>/<i>-ir</i> verbs.

00:02:50.060 --> 00:02:54.460
<v Teacher>Now <i>-ar</i> verbs have the vowel /ah/ as a principle sound,

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:56.540
<v Teacher>a sound that keeps popping up.

00:02:56.520 --> 00:03:10.280
<v Teacher>So, for example, <i>to eliminate</i>. How is <i>to eliminate</i>? <i>Elimination</i>-<b>eliminación</b>-<b>eliminar</b>. Good. <b>Eliminar</b>. So if you want to say <i>I eliminate</i> or <i>I delete</i>,

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:11.879
<v Teacher>how would it be?

00:03:11.879 --> 00:03:13.480
<v Teacher>Think syllable by syllable.

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:17.319
<v Teacher>If you think of it all together it's quite confusing here because you have quite a few vowels.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:18.920
<v Student><b>Elimino</b>?

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:24.440
<v Teacher>Good. You see when you take your time to divide actually the word piece by piece, it's much more digestible.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:26.680
<v Teacher><b>Elimino</b>. Good.

00:03:26.680 --> 00:03:33.560
<v Teacher>Now for <i>he</i>, <i>she</i>, <i>it</i> and <i>you</i> (formal) - we have learned that these group together in Spanish

00:03:33.560 --> 00:03:36.200
<v Teacher>we just use an <i>a</i> on the ending.

00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:37.960
<v Teacher>So how would that be?

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:39.960
<v Student><b>Elimina.</b>

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:44.280
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:44.760
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:47.240
<v Teacher>And we still have the accent on the penultimate syllable,

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:48.200
<v Teacher><b>elimina</b>.

00:03:48.200 --> 00:03:49.320
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:03:49.140 --> 00:03:54.659
<v Teacher>How do you think you would say <i>to last</i> like "it lasts a long time" or something like this?

00:03:54.659 --> 00:04:01.780
<v Teacher>It's not obvious through the word <i>last</i>, but maybe we find something through Latin that helps us work out how to say that:

00:04:03.620 --> 00:04:07.060
<v Teacher>"a period of time", sometimes we call it <i>duration</i>,

00:04:07.060 --> 00:04:07.540
<v Teacher>no?

00:04:07.540 --> 00:04:07.860
<v Student>Yes.

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:09.220
<v Teacher>So how would that be in Spanish?

00:04:10.100 --> 00:04:12.900
<v Student><b>Duración.</b>

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:15.140
<v Teacher>So <i>to last</i> might actually come from this. If it did, how would it sound?

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:16.880
<v Student><b>Durar.</b>

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:19.680
<v Teacher>Yes. And this is the verb, <b>durar</b>.

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:23.440
<v Teacher><i>A lot</i> is <i>much</i> in Spanish; it's <b>mucho</b>.

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:29.680
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>it lasts a long time</i> you can just say <i>it lasts much</i>.

00:04:30.199 --> 00:04:31.720
<v Student><b>Durar mucho.</b>

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.680
<v Teacher>This is <i>to last</i>, <b>durar</b>.

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:38.440
<v Teacher>So how would <i>it lasts</i> be?

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:41.240
<v Teacher>So…

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:42.280
<v Student><b>Dura mucho.</b>

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:45.560
<v Teacher>So you might be talking about a show or movie.

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:48.360
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>it doesn't last a long time</i>?

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:50.740
<v Student><b>No dura mucho.</b>

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:53.060
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No dura mucho.</b>

00:04:53.060 --> 00:04:54.980
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>exaggeration</i>? Exa/juh-juh/, <i>exaggeration</i>?

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:58.100
<v Student><b>Exageración.</b>

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:00.400
<v Teacher><b>Exageración.</b> <i>To exaggerate:</i>

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:01.680
<v Student><b>Exagerar.</b>

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:05.120
<v Teacher>Yeah. So how would you say <i>I exaggerate</i>?

00:05:08.780 --> 00:05:09.820
<v Student><b>Exagero.</b>

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:14.220
<v Teacher><i>He's exaggerating</i>, or <i>she's exaggerating</i> or <i>you</i>-

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:15.100
<v Student><b>Exagera.</b>

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:16.139
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Exagera.</b>

00:05:16.139 --> 00:05:21.020
<v Teacher><i>He's not exaggerating, she's not exaggerating, you</i> (formal) <i>are not exaggerating:</i>

00:05:21.480 --> 00:05:22.840
<v Student><b>No exagera.</b>

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:24.520
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No exagera.</b>

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:25.240
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:25.240 --> 00:05:28.120
<v Teacher>Did you ever hear the word <i>mastication</i> in English?

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:29.240
<v Student><b>Masticación.</b>

00:05:29.240 --> 00:05:29.960
<v Teacher>Did you ever hear it though?

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:30.600
<v Student>Yes.

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:31.080
<v Teacher>I didn't. I mean this is a word-

00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:32.760
<v Student>It's <i>chewing</i>.

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:33.160
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:35.560
<v Teacher>So how do you think <i>to chew</i> would be?

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:36.840
<v Student><b>Masticar.</b>

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:38.120
<v Teacher><b>Masticar</b> is <i>to chew</i>.

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:42.520
<v Teacher>Now I didn't know this word actually and this will happen to many English speakers as well.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:46.919
<v Teacher>You will be able to work out many English words that you didn't know before through Spanish.

00:05:46.919 --> 00:05:54.900
<v Teacher>So this was the way round it worked for me. Because I found <b>masticar</b> first, and then I saw in English somewhere <i>mastication</i>.

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:57.300
<v Teacher>So it can work that way round as well which is useful.

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:01.220
<v Teacher>Another example is <b>morder</b>, which means <i>to bite</i>.

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:06.080
<v Teacher>I learned this in Spanish, and then I saw in some novel I was reading, <i>mordent</i>.

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:07.759
<v Teacher>Oh ok that means <i>biting</i>.

00:06:07.759 --> 00:06:14.159
<v Teacher>You can increase your English vocabulary and what you understand in English just through the Latin that you learn in Spanish.

00:06:13.860 --> 00:06:19.380
<v Teacher>So if <b>masticar</b> is <i>to chew</i>, how would you say <i>I chew</i>?

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:20.340
<v Student><b>Mastico.</b>

00:06:20.340 --> 00:06:21.300
<v Teacher><b>Mastico.</b>

00:06:21.300 --> 00:06:21.700
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:25.860
<v Teacher>And <i>he chews</i> or <i>she chews</i>, <i>it chews</i>, <i>you</i> (formal) <i>chew</i>?

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:27.979
<v Student><b>Mastica.</b>

00:06:27.979 --> 00:06:28.780
<v Teacher><b>Mastica.</b>

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:29.259
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:29.259 --> 00:06:32.060
<v Teacher>Now this is our key sound, this /a/ sound.

00:06:32.060 --> 00:06:36.460
<v Teacher>Now we can add on different sounds to this /a/ to get other versions.

00:06:36.460 --> 00:06:43.020
<v Teacher>So for example, if we add on an <i>n</i> to this /a/, we get <i>they</i> and we get <i>you</i> (plural).

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:46.060
<v Teacher>So in English like <i>you guys</i>, <i>you all</i>.

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:49.099
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>collaboration</i>?

00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:51.500
<v Student><b>Colaboración.</b>

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:52.539
<v Teacher><b>Colaboración.</b> <i>To collaborate:</i>

00:06:52.539 --> 00:06:54.620
<v Student><b>Colaborar.</b>

00:06:54.620 --> 00:06:56.220
<v Teacher>Good. <i>I collaborate:</i>

00:06:56.220 --> 00:06:57.819
<v Student><b>Colaboro.</b>

00:06:59.060 --> 00:07:00.260
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Colaboro.</b>

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:05.060
<v Teacher><i>He/she/it/you</i> (formal):

00:07:05.060 --> 00:07:06.340
<v Student><b>Colabora.</b>

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:13.100
<v Teacher><b>Colabora.</b> You can add on to this an <i>n</i> and you get <i>they</i> or <i>you</i> (plural). So how would it be?

00:07:15.020 --> 00:07:16.140
<v Student><b>Colaboran.</b>

00:07:16.140 --> 00:07:18.300
<v Teacher><b>Colaboran.</b> Good.

00:07:18.300 --> 00:07:20.940
<v Teacher><b>Hablar</b> is <i>to speak</i> in Spanish.

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:21.820
<v Teacher><b>Hablar</b>.

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:25.020
<v Teacher>It's spelled <i>h-a-b-l-a-r</i>.

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:27.020
<v Teacher>What's happening with that <i>h</i>?

00:07:27.180 --> 00:07:28.300
<v Student>It's silent.

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:29.260
<v Teacher>Totally silent.

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:30.140
<v Teacher><b>Hablar</b>.

00:07:30.140 --> 00:07:32.060
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I speak</i>?

00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:33.180
<v Student><b>Hablo.</b>

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:36.940
<v Teacher>So <b>hablo</b> is <i>I speak</i> or <i>I am speaking</i>.

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:38.220
<v Teacher><b>Habla</b> is-

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:43.599
<v Student><i>He/she/it</i> or the formal.

00:07:43.599 --> 00:07:45.039
<v Teacher>Good. <i>You</i> formal.

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:51.199
<v Teacher>So what would it mean if I said <b>no hablan con Pablo</b>?

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:57.120
<v Student><i>They're not speaking with Pablo.</i>

00:07:57.120 --> 00:08:01.680
<v Teacher>Good. <i>They're not speaking with Pablo</i> or <i>they don't speak with Pablo</i>. Good.

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:04.240
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I want to speak</i>?

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.320
<v Student><b>Quiero hablar.</b>

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:11.520
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I'm going to speak</i>? Think of to go on a voyage.

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:15.460
<v Student>Ah, <b>voy</b>.

00:08:15.460 --> 00:08:16.020
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:17.780
<v Student>Yes. <b>Voy hablar.</b>

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:25.220
<v Teacher>Now I'm not sure, because <b>hablar</b> starts with /a/, I'm not sure if you put the <b>a</b> to connect them.

00:08:25.220 --> 00:08:27.060
<v Teacher>Did you?

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:28.360
<v Student>Oh, no I didn't. <b>Voy a hablar.</b>

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:32.360
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:32.360 --> 00:08:34.760
<v Teacher>And when you speak quickly, it will kind of blend together.

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:36.040
<v Teacher><b>Voy a hablar.</b>

00:08:35.959 --> 00:08:41.000
<v Teacher>Maybe it's a fraction longer, <b>voy a hablar</b>, but it will stick together like this.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:41.880
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:48.600
<v Teacher>Now, if we go back to this <i>he/she/it</i> form, <b>habla</b>, and we add an <i>s</i>, we get the <i>you</i> (informal).

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:51.440
<v Student><b>Hablas.</b>

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:54.080
<v Teacher>So this is speaking to one person informally. <b>Hablas</b>.

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:58.400
<v Teacher>When we have one of these little words: <b>te</b>, <b>me</b>,

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:02.320
<v Teacher><b>lo</b>, <b>los</b>, <b>la</b>, <b>las</b>,

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:05.760
<v Teacher>they will come before the changed verb.

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:09.360
<v Teacher>So the changed verb is the one that isn't ending in <i>r</i> anymore.

00:09:09.360 --> 00:09:11.600
<v Teacher>They will come before this verb.

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:19.040
<v Teacher>So if we have <b>quiero</b>, <i>I want</i>, and we want to say <i>I want it</i>, that <i>it</i> must come before the verb.

00:09:19.040 --> 00:09:20.720
<v Teacher>So how would it be?

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:22.399
<v Student><b>Lo quiero.</b>

00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:23.600
<v Teacher><b>Lo quiero.</b>

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:28.320
<v Teacher>But that little word can also go after the complete verb.

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:34.560
<v Teacher>If we say something like <i>I want to see it</i>, we end up actually having an option where we put that <i>it</i>.

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:37.540
<v Teacher>But it doesn't matter; there's no change in meaning.

00:09:37.540 --> 00:09:38.579
<v Teacher>It's exactly the same,

00:09:38.579 --> 00:09:39.699
<v Teacher>you just have the option.

00:09:39.699 --> 00:09:43.139
<v Teacher>So what was <i>to see</i>, which was related to English <i>view</i>?

00:09:43.779 --> 00:09:44.500
<v Student><b>Ver</b>?

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:44.980
<v Teacher><b>Ver.</b>

00:09:44.980 --> 00:09:49.779
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>I want to see it</i> or <i>I want to see him</i>?

00:09:49.779 --> 00:09:52.820
<v Student>So it's <b>quiero verlo</b>.

00:09:52.820 --> 00:09:54.180
<v Teacher><b>Quiero verlo.</b>

00:09:54.180 --> 00:09:54.500
<v Student>Or

00:09:55.020 --> 00:09:56.300
<v Student><b>lo quiero ver</b>.

00:09:56.300 --> 00:09:57.260
<v Teacher>Yeah you have the option.

00:09:57.260 --> 00:09:58.380
<v Teacher><b>Lo quiero ver</b>.

00:09:58.380 --> 00:10:02.780
<v Teacher>But if you have one changed verb all by itself, you don't have the option;

00:10:02.780 --> 00:10:04.620
<v Teacher>it must go before.

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:09.399
<v Teacher>You might say <i>it's important to speak about it</i>.

00:10:09.399 --> 00:10:13.399
<v Teacher>Now you don't need to say <i>about</i> in Spanish, we're going to say <i>to speak it</i>

00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:15.060
<v Teacher>and that's understood <i>to speak about it</i>.

00:10:15.060 --> 00:10:20.020
<v Teacher>So here, in that clause and that bit, <i>to speak about it</i> is only <i>to speak</i>.

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:25.140
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>it's important to speak about it</i> or literally, <i>it's important to speak it</i>?

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:31.680
<v Student><b>Es importante hablarlo.</b>

00:10:31.680 --> 00:10:36.959
<v Teacher>Good. So how was <i>I must</i> or <i>I owe</i>, which is related to the English word <i>debt</i>?

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:38.780
<v Student><b>Debo.</b>

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:41.420
<v Teacher>So <i>I must invite him:</i>

00:10:41.420 --> 00:10:43.580
<v Student><b>Debo invitarlo.</b>

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:45.980
<v Student>Or <b>lo debo invitar</b>.

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:50.780
<v Teacher>Good. So that's the deal with these little words, where we can put them.

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:51.660
<v Teacher>Good.
